main event: On February 16, 1966, two objects were observed at Brunswick Naval Air Station in Maine for 3 1/2 hours.
interesting points: The objects exhibited hovering behavior, sudden starts, and stopping on a dime,One object seemed to disappear suddenly, while the other was seen circling around a plane,The observer described the second object as large and fast, possibly over 100 knots,At one point the objects appeared to be about 150 feet above ground and generated a smooth passage sound,The report concluded that the observed object might have been Jupiter, but more data was needed for a definitive identification.
witness description: The observer provided a detailed account of the sighting and described the objects as having a grayish metal color,One object appeared to be about 30 to 40 feet long and emitted a smooth passage sound.
